	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=6&mid=101173477720509>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=6&mid=101173477720509>RE: Need Some Advice</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=6&mid=101173477720509#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, Jan 22nd 5:27 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=17094><span id=Sage>Kneesmasher</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>397 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Greetings Ironhom,<br><br>The Armor of Ro quests are very VERY involved, require a LOT of faction work, require some significant risks in places such as Mistmoore Castle (Which can be QUITE deadly), require a SLEW of drops that you must obtain, some of the harder of which are No-Drop, and the quests can take a significant amount of time and take LOTS of effort running here and there.<br><br>I did them all, but my main reason for doing them was for the fun of the quests and the fact that Ry'Gorr wasn't even a word in the game yet when I began. I rarely minded that they were taking lots of time and keeping me from experience groups, etc.&nbsp;&nbsp;I enjoyed going to the different dungeons, seeing different places, working on my faction, smithing the actual piece, and I took my time for the most part. I started at level 30 and was done by level 35 and did most of it, with the exception of Mistmoore Castle, with a Druid equal to my level.<br><br>My suggestion is to consider the Ro Quests only if you want to do the Quests. I had a blast doing them and don't regret it for a second. But it's not fast, far far from it, and it is frustrating at times.  I don't believe the quests are worth the armor you receive.  Shame on Verant for that.<br><br>If you just want to do them for the armor alone...it's easier to just buy or obtain Ry'Gorr.  Ry'Gorr is comparable on AC and Stats, with a few more pluses and a few less resistances.  Most people that have actually done the Ro Armor quests are rightfully proud of their armor because of what they went thru to get it, so the price to buy it is usually a bit higher than Ry'Gorr also...at least on Torvonnilous Server.<br><br>My personal opinion is some pieces of Ro Armor are better than others.  The Ro Helm is nice with good AC and Wisdom and will last you a while, so it's worth it.  The Greaves are nice and I actually wore the greaves until level 53 when I was able to take a pair of Deepwater Greaves from Venril Sathir on a KC raid.  Good greaves are just very hard to come by until level 50.  The Vambraces are nice too and the Plague Shark was a fun battle. The Boots are not bad either. Nice AC, nice gold color. <br><br>But the Breastplate, while nice, is probably not worth the effort, in my opinion. You have to kill the Ancille Cooks DEEP inside Mistmoore Castle to loot the Cauldrons, which are No Drop.  This is not an easy task by any means and Mistmoore is a very Deadly zone.  A Dusty Breastplate is just as good, if not better, and can be bought for cheap usually.  The gauntlets are okay, but there are better out there for not much money. Darkmail Gauntlets come to mind for 100 plat or so.  The Bracers do give a descent AC and +5 save magic, but they are probably not worth the effort in my opinion. Had they been +10 magic each, they would be much more note-worthy. A Bracer of Scavenging is very nice for not much cash.<br><br>Just some of my opinions.  With your trio of players you can do most of the quests with just you 3, but Mistmoore will require more fire power/tank power and some serious know-how. The zone is anything but easy.<br><br>And, as a final note, I figure I roughly lost 5 levels by doing these quests, when compared to focusing on experience. I had a Paladin friend of equal level when we began the quests. He quit shortly after beginning and I was 5 levels behind him when I finally completed them.  I didn't mind....but it's something to think about.<br><br>Kneesmasher Ayebulger<br>Dwarven Cavalier<br>Torvonnilous Server<br><br>&quot;Never Mistake Kindness for Weakness&quot;<br><br><br><br></p>&nbsp;<br>Kneesmasher Ayebulger<br>Dwarven Knight<br>Torvonnilous Server<br><br>"Never Mistake Kindness for Weakness"</td></td></tr>
